WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:03.000
Hello, everybody.

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:08.000
I'm Chris Engelhardt, and I'm a Senior Data and AI Operations Manager at Gen Re.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
At Gen Re, I work on a lot of cool and interesting challenges.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:17.000
I oversee building and deploying custom AI applications and infrastructure,

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:22.000
as well as overseeing our global analytics and data science platform, which runs on Posit.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Today, I'm excited to talk to you about bringing my background in social and personality psychology

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.000
to how I lead data science and AI teams.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Before diving into this topic, though, I want to take you back to 2005,

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:44.000
when Nokia was at the peak of innovation, as evidenced here by the N95 model.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:49.000
And as reported in a case study, Nokia soon had some challenges

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.000
because there was a new competitor in the landscape.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.000
Apple had just introduced in 2007 their first iPhone OS

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.000
with a sleek touchscreen, which Nokia did not have.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.000
And obviously, there was some amount of concern going on at this point,

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:08.000
especially among senior leadership.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:13.000
They were putting a lot of pressure on lower-level managers to deliver in a timely fashion.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.000
And what senior leadership was not interested in

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:21.000
was hearing negative news about meeting deadlines,

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:23.000
or the current status of products.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:30.000
And ultimately, this stifled innovation and led to Nokia's downfall,

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.000
at least over the 2005 to 2010 period.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:37.000
What I want each of you in the audience to do at this point

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:41.000
is to put yourself in the shoes of a Nokia manager.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:49.000
And imagine if you worked in a team where you were afraid to speak up.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Imagine if you were on a team where no matter what you thought,

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.000
no matter what you did,

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.000
would be met with belittlement or beratement.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Imagine if your voice didn't matter.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
Imagine if your lived experiences didn't matter, your mistakes and all.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
What would the outcome of that look like?

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:19.000
Well, I think it can lead to some pretty negative consequences

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:22.000
as a direct result of not being able to speak up.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.000
One, of course, and this was evidenced in the Nokia case study,

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.000
is that there's information asymmetry.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
So managers who were on a lower level

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.000
had access to different information, i.e. negative news,

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:37.000
that senior leadership did not have access to.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:41.000
I think also it led to a certain amount of learned helplessness

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:44.000
in the Nokia organization,

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.000
where the idea here is that no matter what you do,

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:50.000
it doesn't matter, you feel powerless to affect some change

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:53.000
and change the current state of your situation.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.000
Taken together with information asymmetry

00:02:58.000 --> 00:02:59.000
combined with learned helplessness,

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:02.000
I think it ultimately leads to poor team performance.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:05.000
And we saw this in the Nokia example as well.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:08.000
And it has some pretty dramatic consequences as a result as well,

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.000
both on individuals' mental health,

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.000
but also on organizational consequences as well.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:16.000
And this is a challenge.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:19.000
And we need a way to address this challenge as a leader.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:23.000
One strategy that I would submit to you all today

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.000
is to think about addressing this challenge

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.000
through the lens of psychological safety.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:33.000
Where the idea here is that the teammates believe,

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.000
so this is a team-level construct,

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:39.000
it's where the teammates believe that the team is safe

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.000
for interpersonal risk-taking.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:44.000
By interpersonal risk-taking,

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.000
I mean that the team feels free to speak up,

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.000
to offer their unique ideas and contributions,

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:53.000
to admit their mistakes and faults,

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
and ask for help.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:59.000
And these are challenging things to do,

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.000
because each of their own in isolation can lead to

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
perhaps other people perceiving you as incompetent

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:08.000
or not an effective teammate.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:11.000
So there's an inherent risk in each of these behaviors.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:15.000
What I want to do is talk about our journey

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.000
on our team and psychological safety.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:21.000
And the start of our journey began about a year ago,

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:24.000
where I presented to our team on this concept,

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.000
as well as the empirical evidence supporting it.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
So I drew on Amy Edmondson's work back in the 90s.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
And in her work, the earlier study,

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.000
she focused on furniture manufacturing companies,

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:39.000
not among technical teams.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.000
And so I thought if I wanted a great chance

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:44.000
of getting the architects and engineers

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:47.000
and data scientists on board with my messaging,

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:50.000
I also had to present something on evidence

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:53.000
among technical teams.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:56.000
And who better to turn to for that than Google?

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.000
As some of you may know,

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:02.000
Google spends millions of dollars

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
on investigating teamwork,

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.000
what makes some teams underperform versus overperform.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
And they actually ran a study back in 2012 to 2014

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:14.000
examining this exact phenomenon.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:17.000
So they included nearly 200 teams,

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:20.000
many of which were technical in nature,

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.000
and they asked them a variety of questions.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:26.000
A lot focused on individual differences.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:29.000
Does it matter how introverted versus extroverted you are?

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
Does it matter if you socialize on the weekend

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.000
with your teammates?

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:38.000
Does it matter your academic pedigree?

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:41.000
Does it not matter?

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.000
What matters is how people work together as a team.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:47.000
I want to draw your attention

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.000
to the bottom of this pyramid here,

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:53.000
where of course they identified a few factors that matter,

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
but chief among them in importance

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.000
is psychological safety,

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.000
where again the idea is that teammates feel safe

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.000
to take interpersonal risks

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
and be vulnerable in front of one another.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:11.000
I wanted to model the types of behaviors

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.000
that I want our team to espouse as well.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:17.000
And I immediately asked for help.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
And the help that I asked for is

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.000
how do we sustain psychological safety on our team?

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
One unique idea that was brought forward during this time,

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:29.000
and this is admittedly two words

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:32.000
you don't see together very often.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.000
We hosted a team anxiety party.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:38.000
Where we started off in this meeting

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.000
with the fears that we all have,

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
just to get the ball rolling.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:47.000
So I shared that I have an irrational fear

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
of getting stuck at the top of a roller coaster.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:53.000
And I love roller coasters,

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.000
but I have an irrational fear of getting stuck at the top.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:59.000
And I also have a really strong fear of bees.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
So if you see me one day stuck at the top of a roller coaster

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.000
surrounded by bees, rest assured,

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.000
I'm not living my best life in that moment.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:11.000
But there was a surprising amount of overlap

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.000
in the fears that we all had.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.000
And it was a very, very powerful and unique team experience.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.000
And I would recommend it.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:23.000
It's a qualitatively interesting experience,

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
really powerful that I think genuinely brought us together as a team.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:29.000
What I want to do now is fast forward to where we're at today,

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
which is in the middle of our journey.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.000
And I think we'll be here in perpetuity

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
because we are an imperfect team striving for perfection.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:41.000
So what can we do to ask for help?

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
And two ways that I recently asked for help is

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.000
in each one-on-one that I have with direct reports or others on the team,

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
I ask them a very pointed question,

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.000
which is, what is one thing we can do today to improve as a team?

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
And I know that our teammates are really thoughtful

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.000
about what they bring forward during that time.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.000
There's a significant amount of reflection

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:05.000
in what is one incremental thing we can do,

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
what's one action or behavior we can take

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.000
to support this talk, believe it or not.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
And I ask for their help in helping me prep

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:17.000
for this very presentation that you're seeing here.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
So what you'll hear in the next few slides are our teammates' voices,

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:23.000
which is exactly what I think you all should hear in this talk.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
When I first joined Genry back in 2022,

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:29.000
we were a team of three, including me.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
And today, a mere three years later,

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:35.000
we're approaching 25.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.000
So we've had some significant growth

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:41.000
and with that, some challenges with that growth.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
And what we do every two weeks is we have a lot of meetings

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.000
that are focused around developer productivity.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
We talk about the development efforts.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:53.000
In these Agile ceremonies, we talk about the current state

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
and what's going on and what's next.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:59.000
And two changes to these ceremonies.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
One change that was brought forth by one of our teammates

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:05.000
was to split those ceremonies or developer meetings by AI product.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
Another suggestion was to align those ceremonies

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.000
with the company objectives so that way people could see

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
visually how the work that they're doing

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
aligns with overall company objectives.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
My takeaway from here is to enable people

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
to do what they do best.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
And if you're a developer, what you're doing best

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:29.000
is probably not sitting idly in meetings.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
You want to be hands-on, developing some artifacts.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:35.000
And to have focus on how and why their work matters

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
so they can see the meaning and the value

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:41.000
of their overall organizational goals.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
I'm sure none of you have been in this position.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:47.000
But we sometimes will work with vendors that from time to time

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
will guarantee off-the-shelf solutions

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.000
to solve all of the challenges that we have

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.000
in a particular use case.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.000
While you might not have experienced that, we certainly have.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
And what we had to do in that scenario

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.000
was to empathize with the users.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
Validate their emotions, right?

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:11.000
Or promise something where the solution could not deliver on it.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
So we created more of a collaborative environment.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.000
We sat side-by-side with individuals across business

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.000
and worked through their specific use case.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.000
And the end result of this, I think, is that it improved trust

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.000
among our stakeholders and accelerated the development process

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.000
that we had for them.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
And as some of you are aware, of course, empathy matters.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
Putting yourself in the shoes of your stakeholders

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
and building and establishing their trust.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.000
I also want to highlight here

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.000
how we've thought about asking for help.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
Because it's not necessarily when you hit a wall

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
you just immediately go and ask somebody to solve it for you.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.000
And that's because I also want to empower our team

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
to experiment, to fail, perhaps even multiple times.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.000
But importantly, to learn through that process.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
And asking for help is never guilted.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.000
It's never shamed. It's never belittled.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:08.000
It's never berated, importantly.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
But, you know, I was in this position once, too.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
I loved having the aha moment.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
Where I've been perseverating on a challenge for days or weeks

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
and then all of a sudden, out of nowhere, perhaps in a dream,

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
the solution comes to you.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.000
And you have that very special, euphoric aha moment.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
And there are few things like that in this world.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
So while I don't want to take that opportunity away from people,

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:35.000
I want to make sure that people know

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
that they have help when needed.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
I next want to turn to psychological safety

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
and some of the key results that we've achieved as a result of it.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:49.000
Starting first with what we call an AI framework.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
And an AI framework is an opinionated approach

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.000
to how we orchestrate back-end services

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
to make AI applications realized for our business.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
And this foundational layer is reused

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.000
across multiple applications because it's modular in nature.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
And it supports today three applications

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:09.000
that we have running in production.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.000
We've also developed some internal genry packages

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
that wrap AI services.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:19.000
So that way folks who are developing with R or Python

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
can use these in a genry-approved way.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
We also do some cool things within here as well,

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
like mock testing and prompt caching.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.000
Additionally, we also have implemented work

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
at the intersection of Azure Databricks,

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.000
which is a big data compute environment,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
remote compute environment.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
Unity Catalog, which can be used for the management

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
and governance of data sources,

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.000
as well as the Azure Data Lake for storage.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:51.000
If you've ever thought that it's always easy

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
to write to the Data Lake, you would be wrong.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.000
Especially when you're at the intersection

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
of modern tools and technologies.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
And I do want to give a shout-out to Edgar Ruiz

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
for his own interesting capabilities with Posit Connect,

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.000
which is the content hosting platform

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
developed and deployed by Posit,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.000
where we offer capabilities to our external clients

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
in the service of facilitating initial

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.000
underwriting decisions.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
And this process alone has helped our clients

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.000
save about 600 human hours per year.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
In closing, the takeaway for me here

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
is that psychological safety is not a luxury.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
It's the foundational piece

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
upon which high-performing teams are built.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
To empower people to speak up,

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:45.000
to empower people to admit their mistakes,

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
to admit their faults, to be a genuine person

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
and to be themselves, bring who you are to work.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
And I think as a leader,

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
what you would want to know about

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
is what can I do today

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
to help create a high-performing team?

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:07.000
And what I would submit to each of you in here

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
is that psychological safety

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
can be a very efficient vehicle

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
to increase team performance.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:19.000
Thank you all for your time.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.000
All right. Thank you very much, Chris.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:25.000
So we have a few questions.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
All right. So the first one

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
is how do you measure psychological safety?

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
So psychological safety,

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.000
if anyone's interested in measuring this on their team,

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
I would encourage you to go visit any of Amy Edmondson's work.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:43.000
She has a seven-item Likert scale

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
that is a reliable and valid measure of psychological safety.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:49.000
We ourselves on our team

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
have not directly measured that more than once

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:55.000
where we had in some of our Agile ceremonies,

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
you know, how safe were people feeling

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
and people were indeed feeling safe, which is encouraging.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
Because, well, people already will know

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.000
that that's what I'm intending to measure,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.000
so there could be some response bias in there.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.000
But you can measure this in reliable and valid ways.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
And again, I would encourage you to check out

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.000
Amy Edmondson's scale on psychological safety.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
It's a great, wonderful measure to use.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.000
It's used nearly ubiquitously

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
in psychological safety research today.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:31.000
Do you plan to implement more measurements?

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
So again, I think there's some tricks

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
with people's expectations to respond in certain ways,

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
but there definitely are ways that we can capture this,

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
and we do often have check-ins with the team

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
on taking a litmus test and how people are feeling and such.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
But yeah, definitely could have more of a quantitative focus

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
on that in the future.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.000
Okay, thank you. We have another question.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
So you were in the enviable situation of building a team

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
from scratch, three people to 25.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
How do you start to turn the ship

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:07.000
to make the workplace more psychologically safe?

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
Right, that's a great question.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
And I will admit that taking a bottom-up approach

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
will be much more challenging than this coming from top-down.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.000
That said, and I've thought about this a little bit,

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
what I would recommend is talking to your leader

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:25.000
or talking to senior leadership

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
and asking them this question.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.000
Are you interested in team performance?

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.000
Who would disagree with that, right?

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
So when they say yes, say, well, guess what?

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:40.000
I have exactly the right way to approach this.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:43.000
So that way you're aligning what they've already just agreed to

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.000
to the actual behavior that you can implement.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
All right, thank you very much.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
A round of applause, please, for Chris.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
Thank you all.

